06619nam a22013335i 9780691225005DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20211996nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2020759419  a97806912250057 a10.1515/97806912250052doi  a(DE-B1597)576256  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aPS325 4aPS325b.P474 1996 7aLIT0140002bisacsh04a811/.5091 aPerelman, Bob, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Marginalization of Poetry :bLanguage Writing and Literary History /cBob Perelman. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©1996  a1 online resource (196 p.) :b5 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tONE The Marginalization of Poetry -- tTWO Language Writing and Literary History -- tTHREE Here and Now on Paper: The Avant-garde Particulars of Robert Grenier -- tFOUR Parataxis and Narrative: The New Sentence in Theory and Practice -- tFIVE Write the Power: Orthography and Community -- tSIX Building a More Powerful Vocabulary: Bruce Andrews and the World (Trade Center) -- tSEVEN This Page Is My Page, This Page Is Your Page: Gender and Mapping -- tEIGHT An Alphabet of Literary History -- tNINE A False Account of Talking with Frank O'Hara and Roland Barthes in Philadelphia -- tNOTES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLanguage writing, the most controversial avant-garde movement in contemporary American poetry, appeals strongly to writers and readers interested in the politics of postmodernism and in iconoclastic poetic form. Drawing on materials from popular culture, avoiding the standard stylistic indications of poetic lyricism, and using nonsequential sentences are some of the ways in which language writers make poetry a more open and participatory process for the readers. Reading this kind of writing, however, may not come easily in a culture where poetry is treated as property of a special class. It is this barrier that Bob Perelman seeks to break down in this fascinating and comprehensive account of the language writing movement. A leading language writer himself, Perelman offers insights into the history of the movement and discusses the political and theoretical implications of the writing. He provides detailed readings of work by Lyn Hejinian, Ron Silliman, and Charles Bernstein, among many others, and compares it to a wide range of other contemporary and modern American poetry. A variety of issues are addressed in the following chapters: "The Marginalization of Poetry," "Language Writing and Literary History," "Here and Now on Paper," "Parataxis and Narrative: The New Sentence in Theory and Practice," "Write the Power," "Building a More Powerful Vocabulary: Bruce Andrews and the World (Trade Center)," "This Page Is My Page, This Page Is Your Page: Gender and Mapping," "An Alphabet of Literary Criticism," and "A False Account of Talking with Frank O'Hara and Roland Barthes in Philadelphia."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aAmerican poetryy20th centuryxHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aLanguage and languages in literature. 0aPoetics. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh  aAdorno, Theodor.  aAltieri, Charles.  aAngelou, Maya.  aArnold, Matthew.  aAshbery, John.  aBaraka, Amiri.  aBataille, Georges.  aBaudelaire, Charles.  aBenjamin, Walter.  aBlack Mountain.  aBrathwaite, Edward Kamau.  aBush, George.  aCaesar, Julius.  aCamus, Albert.  aCicero.  aClinton, Bill.  aCoolidge, Clark.  aCreeley, Robert.  aDavidson, Michael.  aDerrida, Jacques.  aDunbar, Paul.  aDuncan, Robert.  aEigner, Larry.  aEnglish, Jim.  aFagin, Larry.  aFlaubert, Gustav